>>63552067
The reason the "mouse utopia" experiment is full of shit is because sixty years later, when people stopped being awestruck by papers that confirmed their preconceived notions about human behavior, some people tried to replicate them. And either there was something going on that Calhoun's notes didn't mention, or his papers were bullshit, because rats and mice in conditions as identical as the researchers could make them to his descriptions do not behave the way his papers said they did.

You've heard about the "replication crisis," where it has been discovered that over half of scientific papers, mainly in the "soft sciences," which is to say, psychology, sociology, and such, describe results that are at odds with what researchers actually get when they try to do the experiments themselves. One hates to throw around the word "fraudulent" but it's sure starting to look that way.

Oh, and did you see where I said "mainly?" An awful lot of published papers in the physical sciences also turn out to be bullshit when people try to see for themselves. "Cold fusion" was the one you've probably heard of, but it wasn't the only one.

We, and when I use that word, I mean people in affluent Western countries, have been patting ourselves on the backs for decades now. A meme you see a lot, if you look in certain places, is "the sum total of scientific knowledge doubles every twelve months." It's a meme. The sum total of words printed in scientific journals is doubling, but a big swath of them are bullshit, and no one anywhere knows what's real and what isn't. We just know that when scientists try to replicate the results published in randomly chosen papers, an awful lot of the time it turns out to be bullshit. Some fields are 90%+ bullshit. Biomedical research papers almost always turn out to be bullshit when people who know what they're doing try to reproduce and verify them, and it's been going on for decades. We just notice it more, with the Internet.
